 action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="gent"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Arts/Entertainment</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gbook"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="ncat"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Content Types</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:ncolu"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:nrvw"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="nfact"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Factiva Filters</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:nrvw"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="nfce"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">C&amp;E Exclusion Filter</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:nrvw"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001001-20180324-161425"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets><DescTPC fid="de"><DescField fid="ipd">Metropolitan Desk </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Metropolitan Desk; SECTMB</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field">BOOKSHELF</ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Traveling Through Time</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>Not many books about New York begin in the 12th century, but James Carroll's latest novel, ''The Cloister,'' plausibly links the indelible 900-year-old love affair between Abélard and Héloïse to a chance encounter in Washington Heights between a conflicted parish priest and a Jewish refugee from Nazi-occupied Europe.</Para><Para>''The Cloister'' poetically pingpongs between Abélard's abbey in Saint-Denis in the 1100s, elsewhere in France during and after World War II, and Upper Manhattan in the early 1950s.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Mr. Carroll vividly evokes New York in midcentury: The Rev. Michael Kavanagh's pastoral care at a Brooklyn Navy Yard hospital; hints of Irish hegemony being challenged among the congregants at the Church of the Good Shepherd, which he describes as the only Catholic parish church on Broadway in Manhattan; the bustling North River piers where Michael's father worked (he welcomed survivors of the R.M.S. Titanic) and where the starry-eyed protagonists see the S.S. America set sail.</Para><Para>He weaves a patchwork of disparate threads, threads unraveled from clerical vestments, that, when quilted together, spell out the single word that the book embodies.</Para><Para>Mr. Carroll recalls the rigid authority wielded by Cardinal Francis Spellman; the lavish chancery of the Archdiocese on Madison Avenue, which the author justly views as ''an immigrant's revenge'' on the city's Protestants and which, for good reason, was known as the Powerhouse; the jovial, candlelit dinners the clergy enjoyed at Patricia Murphy's restaurant; the muffled culture of sexual abuse that clerics only winked at then; and the ''the heresy called 'Modernism''' that is resonating so publicly and powerfully today.</Para><Para>In ''The Cloister,'' Mr. Carroll, a former priest himself, draws again on the suppressed teachings of Abélard, the theologian whom he invoked in 2001 in his monumental ''Constantine's Sword: The Church and the Jews -- a History,'' his deeply disturbing exploration of Christian anti-Semitism and intolerance.</Para><Para>Mr. Carroll's latest novel begins with Father Kavanagh's chance encounter with Rachel Vedette, a docent at the Metropolitan Museum's composite of several individual cloisters transplanted from Europe to Fort Tryon Park.</Para><Para>Their awkward convergence becomes an incandescent, allegorical outgrowth of the agonizing introspection that Abélard and Héloïse undergo in their search for self-awareness.</Para><Para>Their letters ''show a great contest between two people but also a contest of the two people against the whole rest of their age,'' Rachel says, adding: ''They are humanists. The first humanists.''</Para><Para>Complicated is a word that Mr. Carroll often repeats to describe the protagonists' past relationships and current conflicts. They both look to Abélard in their soul-searching for a lesson on love and life. ''The key to wisdom is this,'' he wrote. ''Constant and frequent questioning, for by doubting we are led to question and by questioning we arrive at the truth.''</Para><Para>.</Para><Para>Looking for another provocative porthole to the past? Try Ben Dolnick's fourth novel, ''The Ghost Notebooks'' (Pantheon Books).</Para><Para>The plot provides a durable framework for Mr. Dolnick's keen eye for detail and his penetrating ear for dialogue. (The narrator says of his girlfriend: ''She was highly attuned to the male blowhard, as a species, for reasons that became obvious as soon as I met her father.'')</Para><Para>An Astoria couple, a musician and a laid-off researcher, trade their dead-ended careers and transplant themselves upstate to a spooky museum that belonged to an eccentric 19th-century philosopher and will now double as their home.</Para><Para>They can't even begin to guess what a museum board member means when she guides them through the dusty old place and says, ''Don't let them trick you into thinking of it as just another creaky old house.'' Is it pride or a portent?</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By SAM ROBERTS </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 The New York Times Company.  All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

